  description: 
  chapters:
  - verses:
    - name: "1: The Shulamite 1:2The word for \u201CShulamite\u201D and the word
        for \u201CSolomon\u201D are taken from the same Hebrew root word; one is
        masculine, the other feminine. The name Solomon occurs seven times in this
        book, which points us to the perfect King, Jesus Christ. We are one spirit
        with our King, united with him. You and I have become the Shulamite."
      title: "The Shulamite 1:2The word for \u201CShulamite\u201D and the word for
        \u201CSolomon\u201D are taken from the same Hebrew root word; one is masculine,
        the other feminine. The name Solomon occurs seven times in this book, which
        points us to the perfect King, Jesus Christ. We are one spirit with our King,
        united with him. You and I have become the Shulamite."
      number: 1
      content: The most amazing song of all, by King Solomon.[[COMMENT(0)]]
      comments:
      - number: <span class="ChapterContent_heading__xBDcs">1:2</span>
        content: "  <span class=\"ChapterContent_heading__xBDcs\">The word for \u201CShulamite\u201D
          and the word for \u201CSolomon\u201D are taken from the same Hebrew root
          word; one is masculine, the other feminine. The name Solomon occurs seven
          times in this book, which points us to the perfect King, Jesus Christ.
          We are one spirit with our King, united with him. You and I have become
          the Shulamite.</span>    "
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: "Let him [[COMMENT(0)]] smother me with kisses\u2014his Spirit-kiss
        divine. So kind are your caresses, I drink them in like the sweetest wine! "
      comments:
      - number: 1:2
        content: "  To enter the doorway of Jesus\u2019 heart we must begin by saying,
          \u201CLet him.\u201D We only bring him a yielded heart and must \u201Clet
          him\u201D do the rest. God\u2019s loving grace means that he will be enough
          for us. We can \u201Clet him\u201D be everything to us. We don\u2019t begin
          by doing but by yielding.      This Spirit-kiss is what made Adam, the
          man of clay, into a living expression of God. Dust and deity met when the
          Maker kissed his Spirit-Wind into Adam. The Word of God is the kiss from
          the mouth of our Beloved, breathing upon us the revelation of his love.
          The Shulamite doesn\u2019t ask him for power, position, or promotion, but
          for a kiss. Intimacy with Jesus Christ is more important than anything
          else he can give us.      Or \u201Cyour breasts\u201D or \u201Cyour loves.\u201D
          This speaks of his saving love, keeping love, forgiving love, and embracing
          love. The love of Jesus cannot be singular; it is so infinite it must be
          described in the plural.      There is a wordplay in the Hebrew, similar
          to a pun. The word for \u201Ckisses\u201D and the word for \u201Ctake a
          drink [wine]\u201D is nearly the same. The implication, as seen by ancient
          expositors, is that God\u2019s lovers will be drunk with love, the intoxicating
          kisses of his mouth. The Hebrew word for \u201Ckiss\u201D is  , which can
          also mean \u201Cto equip\u201D or \u201Cto arm (for battle).\u201D We need
          his kisses to become equipped warriors for him.    "
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: "Your presence releases a fragrance so pleasing\u2014over and over
        poured out.For your lovely name is \u201CFlowing Oil.\u201D [[COMMENT(0)]]No
        wonder the brides-to-be adore you. "
      comments:
      - number: 1:3
        content: "  The Hebrew contains a wordplay with the words \u201Cname\u201D
          () and \u201Coil\u201D ().      Because of the order of the consonants,
          some Jewish sources translate this as \u201CThe maidens love you unto death.\u201D
          (See Goldin, Song, 116; J. Sason, \u201COn Pope\u2019s Song,\u201D 191.)    "
    - name: '4: The Chorus of FriendsThe Shulamite'
      title: The Chorus of FriendsThe Shulamite
      number: 4
      content: "Draw me into your heart.We will run away together into the king\u2019s
        cloud-filled chamber. [[COMMENT(0)]]We will remember your love, rejoicing
        and delighting in you, celebrating your every kiss as better than wine.No
        wonder righteousness adores you! "
      comments:
      - number: 1:4
        content: "  The Hebrew text literally means \u201Cthe king\u2019s chamber
          inside of a chamber.\u201D This points us to the Holy of Holies inside
          the temple chamber.      The Hebrew word for \u201Clove\u201D () is found
          seven times in the Song of Songs (,  ,  ;  ,  ,  ,  ). The Hebrew root
          word for \u201Crejoice\u201D () is a homonym for \u201Cspinning in a circle
          or dance.\u201D The implication is that we dance for joy when we remember
          his love.      The kiss of God pours out blessing over our hearts. It is
          the warmth of his love that convinces us that his heart is turned forever
          toward us. The most common word for worship in the New Testament is  ,
          which means to fall on your knees before him to kiss him. Our worship,
          with deep affection, is his reward.    "
    - name: '5: The ShulamiteThe Shulamite to Her Friends'
      title: The ShulamiteThe Shulamite to Her Friends
      number: 5
      content: "Jerusalem maidens, in this twilight darkness [[COMMENT(0)]]I know
        I am so unworthy\u2014so in need.<JESUS>The Shepherd-King</JESUS><JESUS>Yet
        you are so lovely!</JESUS>I feel as dark and dry as the desert tentsof the
        wandering nomads. <JESUS>The Shepherd-King</JESUS><JESUS>Yet you are so lovely\u2014</JESUS><JESUS>like
        the fine linen tapestry hanging in the Holy Place.</JESUS>"
      comments:
      - number: 1:5
        content: "  Or \u201Cblack.\u201D The Hebrew root word used here for \u201Cblack\u201D
          or \u201Cdark\u201D means \u201Ctwilight darkness\u201D or \u201Cmorning
          gray.\u201D      Literally \u201Cdark as the tent curtains of Kedar.\u201D
          There is a wordplay in the Hebrew, as the word    means \u201Ca dark one\u201D
          or \u201Ca dark place.\u201D This was the name of one of the sons of Ishmael
          and represents our old Adam-life. See  .    "
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: "Please don\u2019t stare in scornbecause of my dark and sinful ways.
        [[COMMENT(0)]]My angry brothers quarreled with meand appointed me guardian
        of their ministry vineyards,yet I\u2019ve not tended my vineyard within."
      comments:
      - number: 1:6
        content: "  Or \u201CMany morning suns have darkened [stared at] me.\u201D    "
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: "Won\u2019t you tell me, lover of my soul,where do you feed your flock?Where
        do you lead your beloved ones [[COMMENT(0)]]to rest in the heat of the day?Why
        should I be like a veiled womanas I wander among the flocks of your shepherds?
        <JESUS>The Shepherd-King</JESUS>"
      comments:
      - number: 1:7
        content: "  She sees her beloved as a shepherd. This is a metaphor of the
          role he takes in her eyes. We need not develop a literal story line of
          a lover and a shepherd, but understand it as a representation of the relationship
          between us and our Beloved, which cannot be described by one symbol or
          role.      The Hebrew uses the verb  , which means \u201Cto wrap [cloak/veil].\u201D
          The Aramaic and Latin Vulgate use the verb meaning \u201Cto wander.\u201D
          This translation has included both concepts.    "
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: "<JESUS>Listen, my radiant one\u2014</JESUS><JESUS>if you ever lose
        sight of me,</JESUS><JESUS>just follow in my footsteps where I lead my lovers.</JESUS><JESUS>Come
        with your burdens and cares.</JESUS><JESUS>Come to the place near the sanctuary
        of my shepherds.</JESUS>  [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 1:8
        content: "  Or \u201Cgraze your goats by the shepherds\u2019 tents.\u201D
          This is a metaphor that speaks of her responsibilities and labors.    "
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: "<JESUS>My dearest one,</JESUS>  [[COMMENT(0)]]<JESUS>let me tell
        you how I see you\u2014</JESUS><JESUS>you are so thrilling to me.</JESUS><JESUS>To
        gaze upon you is like looking</JESUS><JESUS>at one of Pharaoh\u2019s finest
        horses</JESUS>  <JESUS>\u2014</JESUS><JESUS>a strong, regal steed pulling
        his royal chariot.</JESUS>"
      comments:
      - number: 1:9
        content: "  Or \u201Cdarling.\u201D The Hebrew word    is found ten times
          in the Bible and nine of them are in the Song of Songs. The Hebrew wordplay
          is seen in that the words for \u201Ctend the flock\u201D and \u201Cdarling\u201D
          are homonyms.      The finest horses in Solomon\u2019s stables were imported
          from Egypt. See  .    "
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: "<JESUS>Your tender cheeks are beautiful</JESUS>  [[COMMENT(0)]]<JESUS>\u2014</JESUS><JESUS>your
        earrings and gem-laden necklaces</JESUS>  <JESUS>set them ablaze.</JESUS>"
      comments:
      - number: 1:10
        content: "  Her cheeks represent her emotions, revealed by her countenance.
          Her emotional life is alive and pleasing to the king.      Or \u201Cyour
          neck is beautiful with strings of jewels.\u201D The ornaments upon her
          point us to the gifts and graces of the Holy Spirit. Your adornments are
          on the inside ().    "
    - name: '11: The Shulamite'
      title: The Shulamite
      number: 11
      content: '<JESUS>We will</JESUS>  <JESUS>enhance your beauty</JESUS><JESUS>,</JESUS> 
        [[COMMENT(0)]]<JESUS>with golden ornaments studded with silver.</JESUS>  '
      comments:
      - number: 1:11
        content: "  This is possibly the Trinity (\u201Cwe\u201D), which will be
          involved in making every Shulamite holy and radiant.      Gold always points
          us to the divine. God\u2019s golden love and grace adorn her now with beauty.
          The concept of silver in the Bible always points to redemption, the price
          paid to set us free. The cross is a \u201Cstud of silver\u201D planted
          into Calvary\u2019s hill that opened the grace fountain for all the world
          to drink from.    "
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: As the king surrounded me at his table, [[COMMENT(0)]]the sweet fragrance
        of spikenard awakened the night.
      comments:
      - number: 1:12
        content: "  This points to our enjoyment of the Lord as we have communion
          at the Lord\u2019s Table.      See  ;  .    "
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: A sachet of myrrh is my lover,like a tied-up bundle of myrrh [[COMMENT(0)]]
        resting over my heart.
      comments:
      - number: 1:13
        content: "  This tied-up bundle of myrrh is an incredible picture of the
          cross. Myrrh, known as an embalming spice, was always associated with suffering.
          The suffering love of Jesus would be over the Shulamite\u2019s heart for
          the rest of her days. We have the revelation of our Beloved tied onto the
          cross like a bundle of myrrh.    "
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: "He is like a bouquet of henna blossoms\u2014henna plucked near the
        vines at the fountain of the Lamb. [[COMMENT(0)]]I will hold him and never
        let him part.<JESUS>The Shepherd-King</JESUS>"
      comments:
      - number: 1:14
        content: "  Or \u201Cat En-gedi.\u201D    means \u201Cfountain of the Lamb.\u201D
          The Hebrew word for \u201Chenna\u201D has a homonym that can mean \u201Catonement\u201D
          or \u201Credeeming grace.\u201D    "
    - name: '15: The Shulamite'
      title: The Shulamite
      number: 15
      content: '<JESUS>My darling,</JESUS><JESUS>you are so lovely!</JESUS><JESUS>You
        are beauty itself</JESUS>  [[COMMENT(0)]]  <JESUS>to me.</JESUS><JESUS>Your
        passionate eyes are like gentle doves.</JESUS>  '
      comments:
      - number: 1:15
        content: "  The Hebrew word for \u201Cbeautiful,\u201D  , is used five times
          to describe the Shulamite, and three times she is called    (the most beautiful
          of women). Eight times her beauty is extolled. Eight is the number for
          new creation life. Hebrew linguists link this word for \u201Cbeauty\u201D
          to  , which means \u201Cto radiate,\u201D \u201Cto burst forth,\u201D or
          \u201Cto emerge from darkness to project beauty.\u201D It is also related
          to the word  , which means \u201Cto create a sense of awe and wonder\u201D
          or \u201Cto be something special.\u201D When we trace this word    to its
          Semitic roots, we find it has the idea of a specialness or a uniqueness.     
          The Hebrew text literally means \u201CYour eyes are doves.\u201D Some see
          this as a hypocorism, but the dove points us to the Holy Spirit. She is
          commended for seeing him with spiritual revelation as she perceives the
          glory of the cross with its \u201Cmyrrh\u201D (see footnote on v.  ).    "
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: My beloved one, [[COMMENT(0)]]both handsome and winsome,you are pleasing
        beyond words.Our resting place  is anointed and flourishing,like a green
        forest meadow bathed in light.
      comments:
      - number: 1:16
        content: "  The Hebrew word  , usually translated \u201Cbeloved,\u201D is
          taken from a root word that means \u201Cto boil.\u201D The implication
          is that the beloved causes her heart to boil over with passion. In  , the
          Father reveals his Son as \u201Cthe Beloved.\u201D Paul likewise describes
          him as \u201Cthe Beloved\u201D ().      Or \u201Ccanopied bed\u201D or
          \u201Cluxuriant couch.\u201D    "
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: Rafters of cedar branches are over our headsand balconies of pleasant-smelling
        pines. [[COMMENT(0)]]
      comments:
      - number: 1:17
        content: "  Or \u201Ccypresses.\u201D Cedar and cypress were the two most
          common woods used in the construction of Solomon\u2019s Temple.  "
  - verses:
    - name: '1: '
      title: 
      number: 1
      content: "I am truly his rose,the very theme of his song. [[COMMENT(0)]]I\u2019m
        overshadowed by his love,like a lily growing in the valley!<JESUS>The Shepherd-King</JESUS>"
      comments:
      - number: 2:1
        content: "  The Hebrew text reads \u201Ca rose of Sharon.\u201D The word   
          can be translated \u201Chis song.\u201D She now sees herself as the one
          he sings over. The root word for \u201Crose\u201D (Hb.  ) can mean \u201Covershadowed.\u201D    "
    - name: '2: The Shulamite'
      title: The Shulamite
      number: 2
      content: <JESUS>Yes, you are my darling companion.</JESUS><JESUS>You stand
        out from all the rest.</JESUS><JESUS>For though the thorns</JESUS>  [[COMMENT(0)]] 
        <JESUS>surround you,</JESUS><JESUS>you remain as pure as a lily,</JESUS> 
        <JESUS>more than all others.</JESUS>
      comments:
      - number: 2:2
        content: "  This is a thorn bush, which speaks of \u201Cthe curse of sin.\u201D
          See  ;  ;  . On the cross, Jesus wore a crown of thorns, for he took away
          the curse of sin.      The emblem of a lily was engraved on the upper part
          of the pillars of Solomon\u2019s Temple. Lilies are symbols of purity in
          the \u201Ctemple\u201D of our inner being.    "
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: "My beloved is to methe most fragrant apple tree\u2014he stands above
        the sons of men. [[COMMENT(0)]]Sitting under his grace-shadow,I blossom in
        his shade,enjoying the sweet taste of his pleasant, delicious fruit,resting
        with delight where his glory never fades."
      comments:
      - number: 2:3
        content: "  Or \u201Ctrees of the forest.\u201D Trees in the Bible are often
          metaphors for humanity.    "
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: "Suddenly, he transported me into his house of wine\u2014he looked
        upon me with his unrelenting love divine. [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 2:4
        content: "  Or \u201CHis [tribal] banner covering me was love.\u201D There
          are two Hebrew words for \u201Cbanner\u201D:    is the military banner,
          and the one used here is  , the tribal banner, of which there was one for
          each of the twelve tribes of Israel. The Shulamite lives under the banner
          of the tribe of love.    "
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: "Revive me with your raisin cakes. [[COMMENT(0)]]Refresh me again
        with your apples. Help me and hold me, for I am lovesick! I am longing for
        more\u2014yet how could I take more?"
      comments:
      - number: 2:5
        content: "  Or \u201Cgoblet of wine.\u201D King David gave raisin cakes to
          the entire nation of Israel in celebration of the ark of glory, God\u2019s
          presence, coming into Jerusalem (see  ). Additionally, the Hebrew word
          for \u201Cwith raisin cakes,\u201D  , is a homonym that can also mean \u201Cfires.\u201D
          The fires of passion and love are overwhelming.      Or \u201Capricots.\u201D
          These are the sweet promises of grace that sustain us.      Or \u201Cwounded
          by love.\u201D    "
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: His left hand [[COMMENT(0)]] cradles my headwhile his right hand 
        holds me close.I am at rest in this love.<JESUS>The Shepherd-King</JESUS>
      comments:
      - number: 2:6
        content: "  The Hebrew word for \u201Cleft\u201D is  , which can also mean
          \u201Cdark.\u201D The \u201Cleft hand\u201D of the Lord speaks of the mysteries
          of his ways\u2014the unseen activities of grace, which are so little understood.     
          For more on the right hand and left hand, see  .    "
    - name: '7: The Shulamite'
      title: The Shulamite
      number: 7
      content: "<JESUS>Promise me, Jerusalem maidens,</JESUS><JESUS>by the gentle
        gazelles and delicate deer,</JESUS>  [[COMMENT(0)]]<JESUS>that you\u2019ll
        not disturb my love until she is ready to arise.</JESUS>"
      comments:
      - number: 2:7
        content: "  In the poetic imagery of the Song of Songs, \u201Cdeer\u201D
          and \u201Cgazelles\u201D are symbols of the joys of love. The Septuagint
          reads \u201Cby all the powers and strengths of the field.\u201D    "
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: "Listen! I hear my lover\u2019s voice.I know it\u2019s him coming
        to me\u2014leaping with joy over mountains,skipping in love over the hills
        that separate us, [[COMMENT(0)]]to come to me."
      comments:
      - number: 2:8
        content: '  Implied in the context of v.  .    '
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: Let me describe him:he is graceful as a gazelle,swift as a wild stag.Now
        he comes closer,even to the places where I hide. [[COMMENT(0)]]He gazes into
        my soul,peering through the portalas he blossoms within my heart.<JESUS>The
        Shepherd-King</JESUS>
      comments:
      - number: 2:9
        content: "  Or \u201CThere he stands behind our wall.\u201D Fear and religious
          duty will always have a wall to hide behind. The contrast is striking.
          He is free and leaping over mountains, but the Shulamite was enclosed and
          restricted behind a wall.    "
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: The one I love calls to me:<JESUS>Arise,</JESUS>  [[COMMENT(0)]] 
        <JESUS>my dearest. Hurry, my darling.</JESUS>  <JESUS>Come away with me!</JESUS> 
        <JESUS>I have come as you have asked</JESUS><JESUS>to draw you to my heart
        and lead you out.</JESUS><JESUS>For now is the time, my beautiful one.</JESUS>
      comments:
      - number: 2:10
        content: "  The Hebrew word for \u201Carise\u201D () was used by the high
          priest when he spoke to the Levites to take up the ark of glory on their
          shoulders to move it as Israel journeyed through the wilderness (). The
          ark can be a metaphor for the bride, carried on the shoulders of our Bridegroom
          ().      Or \u201Cmy fair one.\u201D This is the Hebrew word for \u201Cfullness\u201D
          or \u201Ccomplete.\u201D He calls us his complete one.      Or \u201CCome
          to me.\u201D See  .    "
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: <JESUS>The season has changed,</JESUS><JESUS>the bondage of your barren
        winter has ended,</JESUS><JESUS>and the season of hiding is over and gone.</JESUS><JESUS>The
        rains have soaked the earth</JESUS>  [[COMMENT(0)]]
      comments:
      - number: 2:11
        content: '  The rains speak of the outpouring of the Holy Spirit. She is
          refreshed and prepared to move out with him.    '
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: <JESUS>and left it bright with blossoming flowers.</JESUS>  [[COMMENT(0)]]<JESUS>The
        season for singing and pruning the vines has arrived.</JESUS>  <JESUS>I hear
        the cooing of doves in our land,</JESUS>  <JESUS>filling the air with songs
        to awaken you</JESUS><JESUS>and guide you forth.</JESUS>
      comments:
      - number: 2:12
        content: "  These flowers may point to the holy lovers of God throughout
          the ages, which after \u201Crains\u201D of God\u2019s Spirit mature, blossom,
          and give forth the fragrance of Christ. Paul was a flower; Peter was a
          flower; and Mary of Bethany was a flower blooming. The sons of God are
          the flowers appearing on the earth out of their union with Christ.     
          Or \u201CThe season of singing has arrived.\u201D The Hebrew word for \u201Cpruning\u201D
          is a homonym that can also mean \u201Csinging.\u201D This translation includes
          both meanings.      This is the turtledove, which is heard only at the
          time of harvest. The turtledove is also an acceptable sacrifice of cleansing
          in place of a lamb. The words \u201Cour land\u201D show the joint possession
          of all things that we enjoy through our union with Christ.    "
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: "<JESUS>Can you not discern this new day of destiny</JESUS><JESUS>breaking
        forth around you?</JESUS><JESUS>The early signs of my purposes and plans</JESUS><JESUS>are
        bursting forth.</JESUS>  [[COMMENT(0)]]<JESUS>The budding vines of new life</JESUS><JESUS>are
        now blooming everywhere.</JESUS><JESUS>The fragrance of their flowers whispers,</JESUS><JESUS>\u201CThere
        is change in the air.\u201D</JESUS><JESUS>Arise, my love, my beautiful companion,</JESUS><JESUS>and
        run with me to the higher place.</JESUS><JESUS>For now is the time to arise
        and come away with me.</JESUS>"
      comments:
      - number: 2:13
        content: "  This text is literally translated \u201CThe fig tree has sweetened
          and puts forth its early figs.\u201D In the language of allegory, the fig
          tree is a picture of destiny and purpose. The sign of a fig tree blooming
          is the sign of an early spring, a new season.    "
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: <JESUS>For you are my dove, hidden in the split-open rock.</JESUS> 
        [[COMMENT(0)]]<JESUS>It was I who took you and hid you up high</JESUS><JESUS>in
        the secret stairway of the sky.</JESUS><JESUS>Let me see your radiant face
        and hear your sweet voice.</JESUS>  <JESUS>How beautiful your eyes of worship</JESUS><JESUS>and
        lovely your voice in prayer.</JESUS>
      comments:
      - number: 2:14
        content: "  This speaks of the wounded side of Jesus, our Rock where we hide
          and rest. When Moses asked God to see his glory, God hid Moses in the cleft
          of the rock. See  .      The Hebrew text literally means \u201CYour voice
          is delicious.\u201D    "
    - name: '15: The Shulamite'
      title: The Shulamite
      number: 15
      content: "<JESUS>You must catch the troubling foxes,</JESUS><JESUS>those sly
        little foxes</JESUS>  [[COMMENT(0)]]  <JESUS>that hinder our relationship.</JESUS><JESUS>For
        they raid our budding vineyard of love</JESUS><JESUS>to ruin what I\u2019ve
        planted within you.</JESUS><JESUS>Will you catch them and remove them for
        me?</JESUS><JESUS>We will do it together.</JESUS>"
      comments:
      - number: 2:15
        content: "  These \u201Cfoxes\u201D are the compromises that are hidden deep
          in our hearts. These are areas of our lives where we have not yet allowed
          the victory of Christ to shine. The foxes keep the fruit of his Spirit
          from growing within us.    "
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: I know my lover is mine and I have everything in you,for we delight
        ourselves in each other. [[COMMENT(0)]]
      comments:
      - number: 2:16
        content: "  The Hebrew wording includes the phrase \u201CHe browses among
          the lilies.\u201D The Hebrew word for \u201Cbrowse\u201D can also mean
          \u201Cto take delight in\u201D or \u201Cto be as a special friend.\u201D
          The same Hebrew word,  , is used in  , \u201CThe Lord is my best friend
          and my shepherd.\u201D    "
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: "But until the day springs to lifeand the shifting shadows of fear
        disappear,turn around, my lover, and ascendto the holy mountains of separation
        [[COMMENT(0)]] without me.Until the new day fully dawns,run on ahead like
        the graceful gazelleand skip like the young stagover the mountains of separation.Go
        on ahead to the mountain of spices\u2014I\u2019ll come away another time."
      comments:
      - number: 2:17
        content: "  This text literally means \u201Cmountains of Bether,\u201D the
          Hebrew word for \u201Cseparation\u201D or \u201Cgap.\u201D This could be
          the realm of holiness, being separated to God. Some scholars say Bether
          was a spiritual representation of a mountain of fragrant spices; i.e.,
          the realm of holiness.  "
  - verses:
    - name: '1: '
      title: 
      number: 1
      content: "Night after night I\u2019m tossing and turning on my bed of travail.Why
        did I let him go from me?How my heart now aches for him,but he is nowhere
        to be found!"
      comments: []
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: "So I must rise in search of him,looking throughout the city, [[COMMENT(0)]]seeking
        until I find him.Even if I have to roam through every street,nothing will
        keep me from my search.Where is he\u2014my soul\u2019s true love?He is nowhere
        to be found."
      comments:
      - number: 3:2
        content: '  The city is a picture of the local church, a place with government,
          order, and overseers. She goes from church to church, looking for the one
          she loves.    '
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: "Then I encountered the overseers as they encircled the city.So I
        asked them, \u201CHave you found him\u2014my heart\u2019s true love?\u201D"
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: "Just as I moved past them, I encountered him.I found the one I adore!I
        caught him and fastened myself to him,refusing to be feeble in my heart again.
        [[COMMENT(0)]]Now I\u2019ll bring him back to the temple withinwhere I was
        given new birth\u2014into my innermost parts, the place of my conceiving.<JESUS>The
        Shepherd-King</JESUS>"
      comments:
      - number: 3:4
        content: "  Or \u201CI hugged him and sank down  .\u201D    "
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: "<JESUS>Promise me, O&nbsp;Jerusalem maidens,</JESUS><JESUS>by the
        gentle gazelles and delicate deer,</JESUS><JESUS>that you\u2019ll not disturb
        my love until she is ready to arise.</JESUS><JESUS>The Voice of the Lord</JESUS>"
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: "<JESUS>Who is this one ascending from the wilderness</JESUS><JESUS>in
        the pillar of the glory cloud?</JESUS><JESUS>He is fragrant with the anointing
        oils</JESUS><JESUS>of myrrh and frankincense</JESUS>  [[COMMENT(0)]]<JESUS>\u2014</JESUS><JESUS>more
        fragrant than all the spices of the merchant.</JESUS>"
      comments:
      - number: 3:6
        content: '  These spices are found in the Bible as ingredients of the sacred
          anointing oil. Myrrh points to the suffering and death of Christ, while
          frankincense reveals the fragrance of his perfect life and ministry.  '
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: "<JESUS>Look! It is the king\u2019s marriage carriage\u2014</JESUS><JESUS>the
        love seat surrounded by sixty champions, the mightiest of Israel\u2019s host,</JESUS><JESUS>are
        like pillars of protection.</JESUS>"
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: "<JESUS>They stand ready with swords</JESUS><JESUS>to defend the king
        and his fianc\xE9e</JESUS><JESUS>from every terror of the night.</JESUS>"
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: <JESUS>The king made this mercy seat for himself</JESUS><JESUS>out
        of the finest wood that will not decay.</JESUS>
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: "<JESUS>Pillars of smoke, like silver mist\u2014</JESUS><JESUS>a canopy
        of golden glory dwells above it.</JESUS><JESUS>The place where they sit together</JESUS><JESUS>is
        sprinkled with crimson.</JESUS><JESUS>Love and mercy cover this carriage,</JESUS><JESUS>blanketing
        his tabernacle throne.</JESUS><JESUS>The king himself has made it</JESUS><JESUS>for
        those who will become his bride.</JESUS>"
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: "<JESUS>Rise up, Zion maidens, brides-to-be!</JESUS><JESUS>Come and
        feast your eyes on this king</JESUS><JESUS>as he passes in procession on
        his way to his wedding.</JESUS><JESUS>This is the day filled with overwhelming
        joy\u2014</JESUS><JESUS>the day of his great gladness.</JESUS>"
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: '1: <JESUS>The Bridegroom-King</JESUS>'
      title: <JESUS>The Bridegroom-King</JESUS>
      number: 1
      content: "<JESUS>Listen, my dearest darling,</JESUS><JESUS>you are so beautiful\u2014you
        are beauty itself to me!</JESUS><JESUS>Your eyes are</JESUS><JESUS>like gentle
        doves behind your veil.</JESUS><JESUS>What devotion I see each time I gaze
        upon you.</JESUS><JESUS>You are like a sacrifice ready to be offered.</JESUS> 
        [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 4:1
        content: "  The Hebrew text literally means \u201CYour hair is like a flock
          of goats streaming down Mount Gilead.\u201D There is great symbolism in
          this verse. Hair is a symbol of our devotion to Christ. Mount Gilead (\u201Chill
          of testimony\u201D) is where the sacrificial animals were kept in preparation
          for temple sacrifices. So a goat coming down Mount Gilead was \u201Ca sacrifice
          ready to be offered.\u201D    "
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: <JESUS>When I look at you,</JESUS><JESUS>I see how you have taken
        my fruit and tasted my word.</JESUS><JESUS>Your life has become clean and
        pure,</JESUS><JESUS>like a lamb washed and newly shorn.</JESUS><JESUS>You
        now show grace and balance with truth on display.</JESUS>
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: "<JESUS>Your lips are as lovely as Rahab\u2019s scarlet ribbon,</JESUS> 
        [[COMMENT(0)]]<JESUS>speaking mercy, speaking grace.</JESUS><JESUS>The words
        of your mouth are as refreshing as an oasis.</JESUS><JESUS>What pleasure
        you bring to me!</JESUS><JESUS>I see your blushing cheeks</JESUS><JESUS>opened
        like the halves of a pomegranate,</JESUS>  <JESUS>showing through your veil
        of tender meekness.</JESUS>"
      comments:
      - number: 4:3
        content: "  The \u201Cscarlet ribbon\u201D in the text is a comparison to
          the ribbon Rahab placed at her dwelling to show the place where mercy would
          spare her life. The color scarlet points us to the blood of mercy, Christ\u2019s
          sacrifice that has spared us. See  .      Pomegranates speak of our open
          hearts of love, filled with passion for God. The Hebrew word for \u201Cpomegranate\u201D
          is  , a homonym for a word that means \u201Cto rise up.\u201D Pomegranates
          were also engraved on the tops of the pillars of Solomon\u2019s Temple
          and sewn into the hem of the robe of the high priest, interspersed with
          golden bells.    "
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: "<JESUS>When I look at you,</JESUS><JESUS>I see your inner strength,
        so stately and strong.</JESUS><JESUS>You are as secure as David\u2019s fortress.</JESUS><JESUS>Your
        virtues and grace cause a thousand famous soldiers</JESUS><JESUS>to surrender
        to your beauty.</JESUS>"
      comments: []
    - name: '5: The Shulamite'
      title: The Shulamite
      number: 5
      content: <JESUS>Your pure faith and love rest over your heart</JESUS><JESUS>as
        you nurture those who are yet infants.</JESUS>
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: "I\u2019ve made up my mind.Until the darkness disappears and the dawn
        has fully come,in spite of shadows and fears,I will go to the mountaintop
        with you\u2014the mountain of suffering love [[COMMENT(0)]]and the hill of
        burning incense.Yes, I will be your bride. <JESUS>The Bridegroom-King</JESUS>"
      comments:
      - number: 4:6
        content: "  Literally \u201Cthe mountain of myrrh\u201D\u2014the emblem of
          suffering love. To become the bride, she must experience Calvary, as did
          her Lord. We must be his co-crucified partner who will embrace the fellowship
          of his sufferings. See  ;  .      As implied in the context and affirmed
          by the bridegroom in v.  , this verse is the first mention of the Shulamite
          as the bride.    "
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: <JESUS>Every part of you is so beautiful, my darling.</JESUS><JESUS>Perfect
        is your beauty, without flaw within.</JESUS>
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: "<JESUS>Now you are ready, my bride,</JESUS><JESUS>to come with me
        as we climb the highest peaks together.</JESUS><JESUS>Come with me through
        the archway of trust.</JESUS>  [[COMMENT(0)]]<JESUS>We will look</JESUS>   
        <JESUS>down</JESUS><JESUS>from the crest of the glistening mounts</JESUS><JESUS>and
        from the summit of our sublime sanctuary,</JESUS><JESUS>from the lion\u2019s
        den and the leopard\u2019s lair.</JESUS>"
      comments:
      - number: 4:8
        content: "  This phrase is translated from the Septuagint. The Hebrew is
          \u201Cthe crest of Amana.\u201D    comes from a Hebrew root word from which
          we get the English word \u201Camen.\u201D This is also one of the Hebrew
          words for \u201Cfaith.\u201D The crest of Amana is the realm where all
          God\u2019s promises are kept and realized. Amana can also be translated
          \u201Ca place of settled security.\u201D (  by J. B. Jackson.)      The
          meaning of the word for \u201Clook\u201D includes \u201Csurvey, inspect,
          look all around, observe.\u201D The bride of Christ is seated on high with
          Jesus and is encouraged to survey all the blessings heaven contains\u2014it
          is a picture of our co-exaltation with Christ.    "
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: "<JESUS>For you reach into my heart.</JESUS><JESUS>With one flash
        of your eyes I am undone by your love,</JESUS><JESUS>my beloved, my equal,</JESUS> 
        [[COMMENT(0)]]  <JESUS>my bride.</JESUS><JESUS>You leave me breathless\u2014</JESUS><JESUS>I
        am overcome</JESUS><JESUS>by merely a glance from your worshiping eyes,</JESUS><JESUS>for
        you have stolen my heart.</JESUS>  <JESUS>I am held hostage by your love</JESUS><JESUS>and
        by the graces of righteousness shining upon you.</JESUS>  "
      comments:
      - number: 4:9
        content: "  Or \u201Csister.\u201D      Or \u201Cyou have ravished my heart.\u201D
          This is the Hebrew word  , which is taken from a Semitic root word that
          means \u201Cto tear bark off of a tree.\u201D He is saying that your loving
          eyes of worship have uncovered his heart and laid it bare, making him vulnerable
          to you. What a description of what happens to Jesus when he looks into
          your eyes. Your worship brings to him such an ecstasy and delight that
          it becomes hard to even imagine. Yet God has placed inside of you the ability
          to ravish the vulnerable heart of your King\u2014not someday in heaven,
          but now, even when you feel incomplete and weak.      Or \u201Cthe jewels
          of your neck [necklace].\u201D These divine jewels are the beautifying
          graces that the Holy Spirit gives to us. They are the \u201Cgraces of righteousness\u201D
          given to the redeemed bride of Christ.    "
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: "<JESUS>How satisfying to me, my equal, my bride.</JESUS><JESUS>Your
        love is my finest wine\u2014intoxicating and thrilling.</JESUS><JESUS>And
        your sweet, perfumed praises\u2014so exotic, so pleasing.</JESUS>"
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: '<JESUS>Your loving words are like the honeycomb to me;</JESUS><JESUS>your
        tongue releases milk and honey,</JESUS><JESUS>for I find the promised land
        flowing within you.</JESUS>  [[COMMENT(0)]]<JESUS>The fragrance of your worshiping
        love</JESUS><JESUS>surrounds you with scented robes of white.</JESUS>  '
      comments:
      - number: 4:11
        content: "  Both the promised land and your heart flow with milk and honey.
          You have become the promised land of Jesus Christ.      Or \u201Clike the
          scent of Lebanon.\u201D    "
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: "<JESUS>My darling bride, my private paradise,</JESUS><JESUS>fastened
        to my heart.</JESUS><JESUS>A secret spring that no one else can have are
        you\u2014</JESUS><JESUS>my bubbling fountain hidden from public view.</JESUS><JESUS>What
        a perfect partner to me now that I have you.</JESUS>"
      comments: []
    - name: '13-14: '
      title: 
      number: 13-14
      content: "<JESUS>Your inward life is now sprouting, bringing forth fruit.</JESUS><JESUS>What
        a beautiful paradise unfolds within you.</JESUS>  [[COMMENT(0)]]<JESUS>When
        I\u2019m near you, I smell aromas of the finest spice,</JESUS><JESUS>for
        many clusters of my exquisite fruit</JESUS><JESUS>now grow within your inner
        garden.</JESUS><JESUS>Here are the nine:</JESUS><JESUS>pomegranates</JESUS>   
        <JESUS>of passion,</JESUS><JESUS>henna</JESUS>    <JESUS>from heaven,</JESUS><JESUS>spikenard</JESUS>   
        <JESUS>so sweet,</JESUS><JESUS>saffron</JESUS>    <JESUS>shining,</JESUS><JESUS>fragrant
        calamus</JESUS>    <JESUS>from the cross,</JESUS><JESUS>sacred cinnamon,</JESUS> 
        <JESUS>branches of scented woods,</JESUS>  <JESUS>myrrh, like tears from
        a tree,</JESUS>  <JESUS>and aloe as eagles ascending.</JESUS>  "
      comments:
      - number: "4:13\u201314"
        content: "  Or \u201CYour shoots are a paradise of pomegranates.\u201D     
          \u201CPomegranate\u201D is taken from a word that means \u201Cexalted.\u201D
          The temple pillars and the robe of the high priest were adorned with pomegranates.     
          \u201CHenna\u201D comes from a root word for \u201Cransom price\u201D or
          \u201Credemption.\u201D The fruit of mercy is seen in his maturing bride.     
          The Hebrew root word for \u201Cspikenard\u201D means \u201Clight.\u201D
          She (the bride) is walking in the light as he (Christ) is the Light.     
          \u201CSaffron\u201D is the crocus, the lover\u2019s perfume, costly and
          fragrant.      \u201CCalamus\u201D is taken from a marsh plant known as
          sweet flag, which produces fragrant oil. The Hebrew word for this spice
          can also mean \u201Cpurchased\u201D or \u201Credeemed.\u201D      Cinnamon
          emits a fragrance that is representative of an odor of holiness to the
          Lord. It was used in the sacred anointing oil of the priests and the tabernacle.     
          This is the incense that would be burned on the golden altar in the Holy
          Place.      Known as \u201Ctears from a tree,\u201D myrrh was a resin spice
          formed by cutting a tree. It is a picture of the suffering love of Christ
          dripping down from Calvary\u2019s tree.      Aloe is considered by many
          to be a healing balm. The presence of the Lord within her is released as
          a healing balm to those she touches. Jesus\u2019 robes smelled of aloe
          (see  ). One of the names used by some for aloe is \u201Ceagle wood.\u201D
          Like eagles, we fly above our wounds, free from the past as we walk in
          intimacy with Jesus.    "
